04080nam a22006735i 9780231555333DE-B159720230502090707.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230502t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021035035  a97802315553337 a10.7312/crow204022doi  a(DE-B1597)650104  a(OCoLC)1374540706  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aGE300b.C766 2022 4aGE300b.C766 2022 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a658.4/083223/eng/202110011 aCrowley, Martin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAccidental Agents :bEcological Politics Beyond the Human /cMartin Crowley. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aInsurrections: Critical Studies in Religion, Politics, and Culture00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Bruno Latour: “We Have to Agree to Talk About War” -- tHorizon 1: Antagonistic Alliances -- t2 Bernard Stiegler: Deciding on the Accident -- tHorizon 2: At the Speed of the Digital Algorithm -- t3 Catherine Malabou: “There Is Nothing Beforehand” -- tConclusion -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the Anthropocene, the fact that human activity is enmeshed with the existence and actions of every kind of other being is inescapable. As a result, the planetary ecological crisis has brought forth an urgent need to rethink understandings of human action. One response holds that the transformations necessary to tackle today’s crises will emerge from the distinctive capacity of human beings to transcend their environment. Another school of thought calls for seeing action as composite, produced by distributed networks of human and nonhuman agents. Yet the first of these is open to charges of human exceptionalism, while the second, according to its critics, lacks effective political traction.Martin Crowley argues that a new conception of political agency is necessary to break this impasse. Engaging with thinkers such as Bruno Latour, Bernard Stiegler, and Catherine Malabou, Crowley proposes an original account of agency as both distributed and decisive. Challenging the prevailing view of agency as exclusively human, he explores how a politics that incorporates nonhuman agency can intervene in the real world, examining timely issues such as climate-related migration and digital-algorithmic politics. A major intervention into ongoing debates in posthumanism, political ecology, and political theory, Accidental Agents reshapes our understanding of political agency in and for a more-than-human world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aEnvironmental managementxPolitical aspects. 0aNaturexPhilosophy. 0aPhilosophy of nature. 0aPosthumanism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/crow2040240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231555333423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231555333/original  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK